- In NoSQL, you dont have joins and you keep data in one blob
- In NoSQL, you have flexibility of schemas. In SQL, you need to have locks  to maintains concistency when adding a  column
- NoSQl has horizontal partitioning.
- NoSQL built for aggregations/ metrics/analytics

NoSQL not used case:
--------------------
- In SQL you have acid, but read after update is problem here. So consistency is a problem.
- Not read optimised to select a particular parameter in the json
- Not built for relations 
- No concept of joins
